One little thing you left out : How he died & I think I can explain it. I noticed a thread talking about the parasite from the second movie on his heart & I can tell you it probably wasn't that. I am going adamantium poisoning BUT it's more complex than that. Anyone who has seen Princess Bride knows where I'm going with this. With how long the metal would have been in his body he would have built up an immunity. That initially made me hit a wall but after the whole thing about GMOs having mutant gene suppressants in them it gave me another idea & that was that Logan's immune system must have been so connected to mutant genetics that if his mutant DNA was suppressed so too would his immune system & any adaption he had to the poison of the adamantium. So in short, his immune system was probably suppressed.

About the Cross that becomes an "X" on Logan's grave, some say that because of X23's mexican background (that is a very catholic country), it might also be a reference to Saint André, an apostle that begged to his killers to not be crucified the same way as Jesus because he deemed himself unworthy, he was a man that regretted some of his deeds but died for his faith and his cross was raised as an "X".

To me it sounds more like a coincidence, it's probably an accidental reference, but even if it's not, because of the religious context (that is historically a sensible topic on pop culture) it probably would never be confirmed by the producers/director.

Historically, the Roman crucifixion was placed diagonally with two intersecting timbres of the same length. This is easier than the Christian crucifix we typically think of, just like the hand thing people get wrong. The iconography we see today came from a guy who owned the Roman empire at around 314: Flavius Valerius Aurelius Constantinus Augustus. In reality, I doubt the writer's main point was to be historically accurate. It seemed more of a head nod to the x-men than an allusion to messianic sacrifice, because the kid probably didn't know anything about the historical details of brutal, old-world executions.
I wouldn't put it past a writer to plant something like that in a movie. Writers tend to read a lot, and know a lot of things. And the Christ trope, or the sacrificial hero, is popular and makes for good fiction. If the writers were going for the Christ trope, does that mean Logan could possibly be resurrected? Wouldn't doubt it.

Where the other mutants? "LOGAN" : Logan is set in 2029, years after Professor X’s degenerative brain disease causes him to melt all of his students’ brains into soup. We don’t see this horrific event in a flashback, but in a heartbreaking scene, Xavier tells Logan that he finally remembers what he did all those years ago. We do see what happens when Xavier suffers a stroke: His brain waves vibrate so violently around him that every living thing freezes painfully. Mutants like Laura and Logan are slightly less affected by this vibration, and though they scream with effort, they can slowly move toward Xavier in order to inject him with his stroke meds. Watching the several strokes Xavier has in the film makes it easy to imagine what it looked like when he accidentally killed his students.

The primary reason Hugh Jackman gave up the role of Wolverine was because of the physical prowess required to play the character in the movie.

Every movie wolverine is in there is at some point a scene where he is shirtless/singlet and he needs to be physically ripped/shredded to portray the character.

The problem for Hugh Jackman was that it takes him longer to get ripped/shredded to attain that 'look' than it does to actually make the whole movie and doing that for 17years is well...exhausting (and unhealthy).

This was the primary reason for retirement, the physical toll it was taking on Hugh Jackman to meet the fans requirements for what Wolverine physically looked like, it's why in contrast actors/characters like Tony Stark/Ironman will never have to worry about this physical toll on their own bodies and thus allow him to play the character till the bitter end, being surrounded by armor etc. know one rants and raves about the 6pack/muscles of Tony Stark/Robert Downie Jr. he is all about the suit (which is ageless).

But I certainly expect to see Hugh Jackman return as Wolverine at some point in the "distant" future after a lonnng deserved rest.

P.S. - It's our own expectations of what we want Hugh Jackman to look like physically as Wolverine that inevitably forced him into retirement.

Hmm. Seems to be a few spoilers in these comments

I am not going to correct any of this shit. There is a lot of rambling and some insights so take it for what it is:

Don't say Alpha flight, there should be a definitive for why Canada. Logan was a failed send-off for the character himself. The pacing was fine, but the ending was shit, the stakes weren't high enough, Charles side story should've been fleshed out, no redemption. In fact, what was Logan's problem? That everyone 'died'? How the fuck did all the mutants die? Only 7 X-Men died from Charles 'mental' happening. Also, why the fuck is he so goddamn old. Where the fuck does Days of Futures past take place? 6 years for Wolverine to fucking fall apart? Get the fuck outta here? What, Adamantium was poising him? It's like a stainless steel. No residue would come the fuck off. And when he said poison, I don't think he meant that literally. So what the fuck happen to him in 6 years? We get old gradually, not just fucking fall off.

And the Wolverine clone villain? WTF? What kind of lazy bullshit is this? This is second to the Silver Samurai bullshit from The Wolverine. Where the fuck are the other mutants? Magneto? etc.?

And Laura calling him dad? There was no fucking bonding at all throughout the fucking film. The best scene was the dinner where we actually get to see the characters react towards each other with some witty banter. Then what happens? I useless water scene for no fucking reason. Then the son gets brutally murdered. Wait, I am not done. THEN Charles gets stabbed on the worst death scene for a most important mutant and the most prominent figure in the entire series. He died like a bitch and he had no redemption which sucks because that backstory should have been better. But back to what I was saying, When a movie is based on travelling across country, the characters are the most important part because they must react toward each other. Also, the reaction also helps the other characters play off one another and a change happens. There was no actual bond for none of them which sucked.

The Shane scene was real shitty foreshadowing and bad exposition.

The ending was so godawful. The stakes were not high enough for Logan. His stupid green shot to help him become powerful was weak. Some guy actually found that bag and the syringe Logan used? Those fucks were ahead of him. But fighting himself (hope there wasn't a metaphor for that) was just plain boring. Did 'The Road' have a climax? Not really, and that fucking journey of a movie ending perfectly.

And last buy not least, let's talk about this fucking R rated. I mean, what a joke. There is a difference between tastefully and just straight up gore. The beheading at the decision to have the head roll in front of the camera to a close up to show the eyes roll into the back of the head was fucking retarded. What was this, a fucking slasher Zombie pic or what? And it wasn't done once either. Then to have the Son just be gutted and laying there with his eyes open was fucking just uncalled for. We know how gruesome Wolverine can be but even in the comics it was done tastefully. It felt like a horror movie. Fucking James got the green light for R rated and went fucking bonkers on how to execute it. Seriously, the F bombs were more or less tasteful and the claws through the head, etc were okay, but know your limits.

Ending scene where Laura turns the cross into the X can be interpreted any way you want. My feelings was that Mangold was trying to reiterate the importance of how Logan was a X-Man and part of the team. Laura drops the X because she sees him as a hero, the same hero as she read in the books. The problem is that Logan does not feel that way. The big concern is that Logan feels this was but do we really know why? Mangold does not really hit on why Logan feels as though he is not really a 'x-man' or 'hero' but the point is not very vivid. Example, what makes this ending better for a Deadpool movie is because throughout the movie, Deadpool constantly reminds everyone that he is not really a hero or debates if he is or could ever be. His constant battle within and his actions throughout it are blatantly shown. If Logan was actually the last Deadpool movie, the ending would make more sense for him. The problem is with this is that throughout the Wolverine movies, Logan never really interacts with any of his X-Men. The first was nonsense, the second was a side story and the third is..well the third. When you do a trilogy, a development of character arc must be complete by the time the final movie ends. If Logan is constantly battling himself of who he is, this would make more sense. Chris Claremont delivers a perfect example when Magnus (Magneto) attempts to fill in the shoes of Charles. Magneto is an amazing Antagonist because he has this internal conflict on what his role ultimately is. His hatred toward homo-sapiens and his relation to his best friend and his beliefs. In the three movies, Logan has no conflict within himself about who he is. In, the beginning of 'The Wolverine', he does, or so it seemed as though they were going in that direction (with him in the forest and the bar fight with the bear poachers). But it stops and he goes to Japan. Frodo is another archetype who goes under a transition in over three books. And this is what makes X2 great for Wolverine. We can see his character become selfish from the mansion and the end. So yes, he has always been an X-Man but it's not there. There is no redemption for him in this. If they would've kept the part where he actually kills the X-Men from the 'Old Man Logan' storyline, this would make so much more sense. And this would have made me feel much more for him, not just him not healing or his claws not fully coming out.

Plus notes: I thought the movie was paced pretty well. The acting was on point, even though Pierce was kind of annoying. The color palette was done well. Music sounded a lot like Cliff M. was part of it. Shit was on point.

All in all this story is like Old Man Logan. If you go into the sense where this is just a story and not actually part of the same timeline then it's okay. My thoughts: Watch fucking Mad Max Beyond Thunderdome. It's much better

To those who are confused about what timeline Logan takes place in:
Original Timeline:
*X-Men First Class
*X-Men Origins: Wolverine
*X-Men
*X2
*X-Men: The Last Stand
*The Wolverine
*The f***ed up future in Days of Future Past (where pretty much every mutant is dead)

New Timeline:
*X-Men First Class (the events of this movie take place in both timelines, because the 60's were never changed)
*Parts of X-Men Origins: Wolverine (the parts before Logan gets adamantium)
*The events in the 70's from Days of Future Past
*X-Men Apocalypse
*The happy future at the end of Days of Future Past
*Logan (where pretty much every mutant is dead)

So, no matter which timeline happens, the mutant race is nearly wiped out either way, thus confirming Hank McCoy's theory in Days of Future Past, that no matter what you do, the timeline will always re-correct it's course (his whole, throwing a rock in the river metaphor).

Unknown Timeline:
*Deadpool- It is unknown which timeline Deadpool takes place in, considering it's set in modern times (2015 or 2016), and the fact that Wade Wilson is about the same age that he was in Origins (which is set in the early 70's), and the fact that we have a different Colossus, it's entirely possible that Deadpool takes place in its' own timeline completely, and that the sequels and future X-Force movies will be completely separate from the X-Men timelines (there will be no more movies set in the original timeline, which I thought was obvious after Days of Future Past, but apparently a lot of people didn't get the memo, because a lot of comments are people trying to convince others that Logan is set in the original timeline, which it is in fact not.

If you remember, the child says that the green liquid speeds up Logan's healing BUT only in small doses. Taking too much can be lethal. At the end when Logan is saving Laura & her friends, he knows he is too weak to take on the bad guys as he is, so he takes the whole bottle of green liquid and injects it into himself, thus giving him full strength as it's rapidly heals all his injures, but only for a certain amount of time. As Logan is fighting and being injured, the green liquid is slowly wearing off. He's becoming weaker as he was before. When X-24 impales him with the tree, the green liquid has run its course -- leaving Logan much more injured than before, and since he took all the green liquid, he now dies as one would from overdosing on that green liquid -- just like the child had said earlier on. Logan knew taking all the green liquid would be his end, but essentially he chose to give his life for his daughter and the next generation of mutants. Extremely heartbreaking and a very well done film. One of my favourites, for sure.

This is because his consciousness was transported from the events of 1973 straight to 2029 "Sunshine days". It is shown by him waking up looking confused and then meeting Prof. X who then says something along the lines of: "Welcome back. I was wondering when you would return". Logan and Prof. X are the only ones who know about the sentinel timeline. Logan's past consciousness that he had 'possessed', if you will, lived through the second timeline's in between years. The present day (for 1973) Wolverine starts to take over his own body again and he doesn't have a clue who Charles is or what is going on. The same thing would happen after they fished the poor bastard out of the river. He'd have no recollection of anything that had gone on over the past few days.

Hell, it could be that after Mystique realised he had no clue as to what he'd apparently been doing, she cut him loose. Chalked it up to Charles wiping his memory. Or.. y'know, brain damage on account of having been underwater for such a significant period of time.

A quick search on Google reveals:

" Depending on how you define "served" this is actually incorrect. If by "served" you mean combat than you may be right, but this is not the definition used by the United States Department of Defense. They use the word serve to mean being deployed to an active theater.
The 97th US Infantry was pulled out of Europe after some 41 days of combat to be in the first wave ashore in the D-day invasion of the Japanese mainland. When the Japanese surrender came they were in theater aboard ships waiting for the invasion to green light. Instead they became some of the first solders ashore as the occupation force, and given various demilitarization & intelligence tasks as part of the occupation.
For this the members of the 97th during this time period were all awarded the Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal acknowledging their service in that theater.
I know this, because my grandfather was the radio operator of HQ Co, 386th Reg, 97th Inf, 1st US Army. His time in the 97th actually got him all three of the WW2 campaign medals. "

-- sg92i from the subreddit link: (https://www.reddit.com/r/AskHistorians/comments/25tr9r/during_wwii_were_there_any_allied_units_that/)

Furthermore, the same thread discusses people in Special Ops even back during WW2 who saw combat in both European and Pacific theaters.

I'd also like to ask why you write X-Men and X2 for 2003 -- for one thing, if you take the 'not so distant future' literally, for X1 then you should also take it for X2. It seems there's some span of time between X1 and X2, but they remain ambiguous about it on purpose. Also, deleted scene in X3 does show that Wolverine returns to that same Canadian bar from X1, so you're actually spot-on with him being in Canada in the beginning of The Wolverine.

Finally, I don't think Professor X in the end-credits of The Wolverine and the future-scenes of DofP are really Charles in a new body, so much as he is a mental projection -- like he 'exists' only in his astral form the way his students (the X-Men) envision him as (in X1 when he is in his astral form he can walk, but again this is an astral projection taken from the way others remember him as). In other words, he still exists but as a mental Jungian archetype who is able to somehow influence the living through the people who remember him. Which is probably how James McAvoy really sees Patrick Stewart and has a conversation with him. That's just my fan-theory at least. However, in X-Men Origins, Prof. X is Patrick Stewart badly CGI'd younger, and he is standing. A few years later, in the flashback to Jean Grey's origin in X3: The Last Stand, we have badly CGI'd younger Prof X and Magneto, where the Professor is also walking. But none of this makes sense because according to your timeline Charles gets paralysed in 1962 during the Cuban Missile Crisis, and clearly haven't met Magneto when he is "17 years old." Ergo, if we are to believe a somewhat insane old mutant, 2000's X-Men and X-Men First Class could not have happened in the same timeline.

Also, "Sunny Days of Future Past" not "Days of Future Sunny Days" that's just weird. What's cool about 'No New Mutants' is that it reminds me of M-Day from the comics, and the whole "No More Mutants" thing that Wanda created in the comics. If this is true, and 2009 marks the end of new mutants -- that means it corresponds to the somewhat same year as X-Men Origins Wolverine got released. That movie, according to this fan, was so toxic that it rendered an entire fictional species extinct.

Few things I'd like to add to the overall discussion:

1) If Logan had been fighting in Europe during WWII and had been found out for his healing factor, it would make some logical sense that he would go AWOL and relocate to Japan (kind of).
2) WHY DIDN'T SABERTOOTH RECOGNIZE LOGAN IN X-MEN 1? THEY'VE BEEN HALF BROTHERS FOR A CENTRY AND A HALF AT THIS POINT!
3) Charles wakes up allegedly in his twins body at the end of X-Men 3, this body is likely chosen because it's a genetic match for Charles BUT the muscles would have likely atrophied to the point of permanent paralyzation. Hence why Charles is paralyzed in later films.
4) At the end of Days of Future Past, it would stand to reason that a 1970's Logan would see "William Stryker" (played by Mystique) and build some level of trust with him as they fished Logan out of the water, keep in mind this is NOW the consciousness of 1970's Logan as opposed to the consciousness of 2023 Logan. So an oblivious Logan is fished out of a lake from a guy that looks like William Stryker, the real William Stryker hears about this and rushes over late, and Mistique ducks out without being noticed. The Real William Stryker keeps tabs on Logan over the next decade, begins doing his experiments, eventually perfects them and later convinces Logan to take part in the 1983 experiment in X-Men Apocalypse. Logan gets his adamantium claws back in the new timeline. His being saved by Gene Gray could also lend to a subconscious "Florence Nightingale" effect for later films, that plus he actually fell for her in a previous life that no one else remembers.
5) In the first time line (I.E. the beginning of Days of Future Past), Logan technically lost his Adamantium claws in The Wolverine movie and should NOT have had them. But oh well...

I would that Days of Future Past doesn't fully erase the parts of the timeline from 1973 to 2023, it just greatly alters the events so they are less...sucky(?) for the characters.  My main reason for thinking this is that in X-Men and X-2, Jean's hair is brownish, but when she returns in Last Stand as Phoenix it is a vibrant red color. At the end of Days of Future Past, it is also this red color, so I interpret it as she has dealt with the Phoenix, but wasn't consumed by it as in the previous timeline. So the initial 3 X-Men movies "still happened" just the events are a bit different than we remember them. (This sort of thing happens all the time when they retcon comic book timelines).  Of course, this is all just how I interpret these films.

I actually think that there are 5 timelines. It's the only way in my head to avoid all inconsistency across the film series.

1: x men origins wolverine, it's own timeline , this is because there are tons of inconsistencies in this film when compared to the rest of the series, some examples are, a) sabertooth being wolverines brother, but looking completely different and with a different personality than in X1, also he doesn't recognise wolverine. And b) wade wilson being alive and well 40 years before deadpool.

2: the original movie trilogy is its own timeline. I say this because of the inconsistency with these films when compared to first class, ( Eric and Charles meeting at age 32, not 17 like stated in X1, mystique being charles' adoptive sister, despite never mentioning this in the original trilogy, Charles walking, bald and friends with Eric in the 70s in X3, and so on..)

3: The timeline with first class in it, this is the timeline that we see the wolverine take place in, the future scenes of the dystopian future of DOFP too. In this timeline, events similar to the original trilogy occured, jean and the professor died. The professor was resurrected somehow offscreen ( there is an explanation given somewhere but it's shit ).

4: the diverged timeline that is created in DOFP, this includes x men apocalypse and deadpool. Everything before 1973 in this timeline stays the same.

5: Logan on its own timeline, but one where Charles was born 9 years later, circa 1939. He mentions he's 90 in Logan, where he should be 99, and mentions watching "Shane" first when he was around Laura's age (11 ish) shane came out in 1953. Events similar to the original trilogy happened in this timeline also (he mentions events from X1 at the Statue of Liberty) also mutants stopped being born around 2004.

This is the only way to view the men timeline where there are no plot holes or inconsistencies

Note: I'd say the Days of Future Past (DoFP) timeline starts before Wolverine went to Vietnam with Sabretooth.

So, narratively speaking It would seem that throughout their lives Sabretooth and Wolverine would part ways from time to time and get together every once and a while, particularly for war. Now, the Vietnam war went until 1975. So, since it had been so long since WWII... maybe Sabretooth was getting bored; killing randoms during the Flower Children movement and was itching to be a part of another huge war. So he calls Wolverine who's just floating along in life, getting into trouble (for bang'n the boss's daughter and such) and thinks getting out of town is probably a good idea. So he goes to Vietnam with Sabretooth where he meets Stryker and so on in the X-Men Origins: Wolverine (XMOW) timeline. But, with DoFP happening... Sabretooth and Wolverine's reconnecting for XMOW in Vietnam doesn't happen.

So, what was Sabretooth doing that whole time wondering where the hell his brother is? I pray he's in Logan in some way. Even if it's just a reference.

X Men Origins was not in the 70's, it was in the 80's. In the very first X-Men movie, Xavier mentions that Logan's memory has been gone 15 years, that would put it around 1985-1988 when he got the adamantium skeleton and lost his memory, the same time it's shown in Apocalypse. It's never made clear how long Logan and Victor were in the military prison or on Team X. As for the confusion of why Logan is in America in 1973 for DOFP, it's likely this was during his time on Team X, and he was probably on leave or something, without a mission for the time being. This also explains how he still got recruited into Weapon X despite Mystique pulling him out of the river. Since Logan was already on Team X beforehand, Stryker already knew him and probably tracked him down and brought him back.
Also, it's been stated that the man whose body Xavier took over was his braindead twin brother, that's why Xavier's new body at the end of the Wolverine still is Patrick Stewart.
The only things that make no sense is how Xavier's new body is still paralyzed or how Logan went from the European Theatre to the Pacific Theatre in only a little over a year

Part of me wonders if the"event in Westchester" might be a reference to Marvel's Onslaught character. Onslaught was created when Charles Xavier was forced to "shut down" Magneto's mind to keep him from killing Wolverine. (In the comics continuity, Wolverine lost his Adamantium when Magneto liquefied the metal in Logan's body, and magnetically pulled it out through his flesh. Youch!) *SPOILER ALERT/LOGAN THEORY* Sooo I don't have the greatest of memory with these types of things, but I have been watching several videos talking about Logan easter eggs and potential future plot lines. There is one detail that I haven't heard anyone touch on yet that I'd like to hear more about. It was a subtle detail in the movie I barely believe I noticed it, but I'm POSITIVE it is legit (too many connections made in the movie hinting at it). Each video I've watched talks about mutants not being born anymore (one even used the terminology of Dr. Rice "cornering the market on mutant weapons") but no one has said HOW. Rather than jabbering on, from what I understood in the movie it is the CORN!! When Logan helps the rancher/farmer Munson go fix their waterline, they have a conversation about this cooperate grown CORN; but people aren't eating it off the cob, it gets into their digestion as CORN syrup when they drink soda and eat sweets..... Dr. Rice brings this up again near the end when he starts "monologuing" to Logan. I am paraphrasing, but he mentions something like "we learned how to suppress the mutant genes through things like soda, etc;" (hinting at CORN syrup)..... I think this also helps to understand the "Logan" movie being part of the original 3 X-Men movies, since they would have contained the most painful memories in Wolverine's life to lead up to the despair he feels (rather than it getting wiped away by Days of Future Past) AND X-Men Last Stand brought about the discovery of a "CURE" (starts with a C just like CORN; coincidence? I THINK NOT!!) for the Mutants. After the destruction caused in those 3 X-Men movies, it is believable that the government would take the freedom to choose from the mutants as to whether they want to be cured or not, and force their genetics to conform to their wants. How do I account for Xmen: Apocalypse's credit scene???? Who cares; it's all speculation on my part anyhow... I just want to hear more about this CORN!!!!

+Sophia Wilson
The way clones work in X-Men (as well as in real life) one person passes on the entirety of their DNA instead of just half.
Laura was born biologically, she just shares no traits with the woman who gave birth to her.
The best way to put it (linguistically) is that Laura is not Logan's daughter, she is his clone. However, it would not be incorrect to call her his daughter, because from a biological point of view she essentially is.
The same is true of the opposite, although I would argue that it is more correct to call Logan her father, since (again, linguistically) there isn't a universally agreed upon term for the genetic source of a clone.
Progenitor, maybe? That would work, but father works well enough already.

Not to mention that humans do have a biological imperative to protect their family members (which she is, regardless of what their specific relationship is) and younger people look to their elders for protection and affection, so Laura's emotional response to Logan would likely make her shy away from the clinical use of words like clone or progenitor anyway.

I would LOVE to see another movie staring X-23. There is, unfortunately, a slight hitch in this effort: timeline.

Laura's debut in the X-Men universe comes in the FUTURE where no new mutants are being born and all the old X-Men are dead. This poses a challenge for movie makers, since you can't have Laura join an X-Men team with Cyclopes and Storm without some convoluted explanation like sending her back in time.

Sure, they could just make a sequel about Laura and the band of mutants she was traveling with at the end of "Logan" where they'd likely become the "New X-Men", but how many people are you going to get to come watch a movie about a bunch of new characters they know nothing about? It could happen, but it would be very difficult. You could reboot the franchise again and tell a new story where Laura was born back when the X-Men were still active, but how willing are people going to be to watch yet ANOTHER reboot of the X-Men under Fox ownership?

The strength of the Logan movie is also it's weakness. This was intended to be a "last hurrah" for the X-Men universe and so they left nothing on the table. There was no universe building because they had no intention of making a sequel for it.

This is so true. Logan, at least for me, ended the superhero genre phenomenon that ironically started all the way back with X-Men in 2000. I feel like every subsequent superhero movie won't feel the same after this film. Along with Hugh Jackman (the man who's been with us through the entire run of comic book movies dominating Hollywood), Logan represented the fatigue of being a hero and, nearing the end, finding one last thing to fight for and discovering inner peace. I'm not saying I won't see any more comic book movies after this, but I believe I've found the perfect resolution to this phenomenon and don't think any subsequent movie in this genre will feel the same. I think the first Ironman marked the beginning and the end of Superhero movies in general. Everything before and after it just seemed kinda meh. The way it was written and executed made it feel like a TRUE superhero movie that still fits in well with other live action genres, meaning it doesn't necessarily have to be considered a superhero movie and that's how it should be when it comes to bringing a comic book to life, not super cartoonish because that's what animators are for. The movie's drama and action sequences weren't over the top and they even elected the perfect candidate to portray a likeable, narcissistic smartass (a character who also isn't over the top, who could also exist in real life) that learns his lesson and matures from his hellish experience when he realizes how arrogant he was. This made the build up to the final act even better because each character had their own unique personalities and motives that gave off a Shakespearean vibe yet still seemed alive, relatable and fun to the audience. Not to mention its take on modern day terrorism and how accurate the movie was when exploiting its dark nature even though it was overall a bright film.

There were quite a lot of personal, grounded superhero movies in the 90s that didn't have bombastic action/ visuals and had very good plot with emotional depth, like Dark man, Robocop, Terminator 2(yes, I consider it a superhero movie), and The Crow. How was this an end of an era for superhero films?

@ian74747
That's a dangerous question if you haven't seen the film, yet.

Well, in the 80's, Christopher Reeve's Superman opened up a new field for movies to explore. 1989 Keaton's Batman gave Comic Book Based movies a different more darker tone of light in which a story can be told on film, and the 1999-2000's X-Men busted the flood-gates open for Super Hero/Comic book-novel based movies. Jackman symbolizes that 2000 era that sparked what Hollywood back then didn't think could be done. To make a Comic Book based movie on a Marvel title that not only follows the story of 1 protagonist but a team of "freaks/mutants" that most people back in the early 2000's main stream-wise didn't really know who they were unless you were a Comic Book aficionado or light reader. Hugh Jackman's R Rated Logan is what Wolverine should have been all along and they finally got to show that side of the character on film (thanks in large part to Deadpool too BTW). End of an era. No more "comic book movies can't be rated R" non-sense. Let's start to finally put the Comic book story lines we all love on film without worrying about what rating it should get.
X-Men and definitely Spider-Man (2002) paved the way for superhero movies in the early 2000's
It's more the end of an era for X-Men movies specifically.

Regardless of the soft reboot that was DOFP, First Class is a prequel regardless of timeline. The happy ending of DOFP is the most recent event in the X-men universe before Logan. Apocalypse is a sequel to the happy ending in the 70s of DOFP which will lead to the the first and second X-men movies (that are still canon according to Fox). DOFP happy ending deleted the Sentinel outcome as well as the Last Stand, which is why Scott and Jean are alive at the end. The original timeline - First Class > Mystic kills Trask in the 70s > X-men > X2 > The Last Stand > The Wolverine > Sentinels Taking over 2023. Logan can't take place here due the Sentinals taking over the world instead of it being normal (as it can get atleast).

The new timeline as of DoFP is something like: First Class > Mystic does not kill Trask, 70s > Apocalypse, 80s > 90s X- men movie being worked on > X-men > X2> The Wolverine > present day events like DeadPool > 2023 DOFP happy ending. Logan picks up 5yrs from then, yet refers to many of the events from the original Xmen movies. It has been proposed that Logan might take place in an 3rd timeline, as it is a send off to Hugh Jackman as Wolverine.

Definitely X1 most of the events remained the same. X2 less so as Jean Grey wouldn't have died. Obviously X3 never happened and probably The Wolverine too as that film requires Logan not be in the X-Men anymore due to Jean Grey's death which of course never happened.

I respect Jackman's devotion, and his appreciation for the role of Wolverine, however, it isn't any exaggeration to say that the entire X-Men series since 2000 has been unfairly biased toward Wolverine. Instead of getting a faithful adaptation of the comics, telling stories about groups of X-Men from generation to generation, the past 17 years has thoroughly just been about serving the character of Wolverine, at the expense of countless other characters (namely Cyclops, Rogue, Storm, Kitty Pryde, Colossus and Iceman). Bryan Singer's first two X-Men films are respectively great and good, whereas after that the series became relatively flat and disorganised, going in all sorts of random and pointless directions. With the exception of just the 2000 film, and to a degree X-Men 2, the X-Men series has been a complete waste of time, including Logan (2017).

코믹스와 전작에 밝혀진 몇가지 사실을 통해 힐링팩터를 잃은 이유를 찾을 수 있습니다. 로건은 올드맨로건, 울버린의 죽음 등을 베이스로 하고 있는데요. 올드맨로건에서는 기차선로에 목을 내놓고 자살하려는 시도로 인해서 극심한 상처를 입고 그때문에 힐링팩터를 잃게되고, 울버린의 죽음에서는 핵폭발을 막으면서 폭발을 막으며 방사능에 노출되는 고통을 겪었기에 힐링팩터를 잃게 된다는 설정을 가지고 있습니다. 그런 내용은 전작인 영화 더울버린에서도 나옵니다. 영화 마지막에 거의 죽음에 다다르게 하자 힐링팩터를 잃는 설정이나오죠. 아래에 논쟁에서처럼 유전자조작인거는 전작에 비추어봐서는 개연성이 떨어집니다. 줄거리알려줌 님이 주장하는 프로페서x 때문이라는 주장은 극심한 고통에서 힐링팩터를 잃는다는 류의 설정과는 맞아떨어질지 모르겠지만, 전작이나 코믹스와의 스토리전개 특히 더울버린과의 연결이 없다고 보여집니다. 미국의 리뷰어의 경우 핵폭발 이후에 힐링팩터를 잃은 것이라고 주장하는 사람(Phil Hornshaw)도 있더군요. http://www.thewrap.com/logan-whats-wrong-wolverines-incredible-healing-powers/ 아무튼 영화상에 내용에 명확하게 나온 내용은 없으니까 토론의 여지는 열어두어야 한다고 생각합니다.

더불어 줄거리알려줌 님께서 만든 영상에 '라고 추측됨' 이라든가. '명확하지 않음' 이런류의 내용을 넣었다면 어땠을까라고 생각합니다. 또한 리뷰어로서 전작영화나 원작인 코믹스에 내용을 기반으로 주장을 한다면 사람들이 더 잘 받아들일거라고 봅니다. 근거없이 혹은 어차피 같은 수준의 추측으로 내말이 맞다 식으로 주장하는건 다수의 사람들이 보는 리뷰어의 주장으론 적합치 않습니다.

Goodbye Logan. I believe that there will be people who are upset that The Wolverine dies at the end of this movie, but for me it was for the best. Hugh Jackman has played the part for 17 years and he just can't keep this up for ever. Sure, lots of other characters have been successfully played by multiple actors. James Bond is the first that comes to my mind but there are plenty of others. This was not a typical superhero/comic book movie. This was a movie about people first and foremost. They struggle with the same things we all struggle with, just in their own way due to their special nature. And they die, just like all of us, leaving behind people who we care for and who care for us. Laura learned to love Logan, and he loved her in his way, which was a little rough. It takes until the very end for this to happen, but the relief I felt when that child called him 'daddy' just shook me to my core and I wept real tears. Everyone should see this movie.

P.S. The Wolverine mantle should NOT go to another actor to continue the Logan character but to Dafne Keen as Laura/X-23. If she can keep it up for 17 years, she will still only be 28 at that time.
